                                <condition>This pillar was reused as a lintel in the construction of a souterrain. The edges of the stone are very rough and uneven.</condition>
                            </supportDesc>
                            <layoutDesc>
                                <layout>The inscription reads upwards on the dexter angle of one of the flat faces occupying roughly the middle third of that angle.</layout>
                            </layoutDesc>
                        </objectDesc>
                        <handDesc>
                            <handNote>The inscription was <q><rs type="execution" key="scratched" ref="https://www.eagle-network.eu/voc/writing/lod/9.html">cut</rs> in fine scores</q> (Macalister 1945, 73). Macalister remarked that <q>the notches of the final I are rather long, and misled early decipherers into reading the letter as Q. Brash makes the A into O, but there is only one notch</q> (1945, 73). The strokes are so fine that they appear to have been made by a saw-like implement, with breaks in the strokes where the stone surface is uneven.
                                <height/>
                            </handNote>
                        </handDesc>
